.H 1 "Configuring the Cache Manager"
.iX "-[" "Cache Manager" "configuring"
.iX "-[" "Cache Manager" "about"
.iX "-[" "client machines" "requirements" 
.P
This chapter describes the configuration of any machine that is to serve as a
DFS client machine.  All DFS client machines must do the following:
.ML
.LI
Run the set of modifications known as the \*VCache Manager\*O in the kernel.
The Cache Manager enables the client to access DFS.  You can control several
aspects of Cache Manager and client performance by configuring the Cache
Manager as described in this chapter.
.LI
Run the \*Ldfsd\*O process, which initializes the Cache Manager by transferring
DFS configuration information into kernel memory.
.LI
Run the \*Ldfsbind\*O process, which resolves CDS pathnames for the Cache
Manager and accesses user authentication information necessary for effective
communications with server machines.
.LI
Provide local disk space or memory sufficient to house configuration 
information and a cache.
.LE
.H 2 "An Overview of the Cache Manager"
.iX "-[" "tokens" "about"
.P
The Cache Manager fetches and caches files from File Server machines on behalf
of application programs that are running on client machines.  To locate a file 
to be retrieved, it first contacts the Fileset Location Server (FL Server) to 
learn the location of the fileset that houses the file; to retrieve the file, 
it then contacts the File Server machine that houses the file.  The File 
Exporter on the File Server machine delivers the file, which the Cache 
Manager stores in the client machine's cache, which is an area of local disk 
or memory designated for temporary storage.  Once the data is cached locally, 
the Cache Manager can access it as quickly as it can a local file.
.P
The Cache Manager verifies that its cached files match the central copies at
File Server machines by keeping the tokens that the File Exporters send with
the files.  A token acts as the File Exporter's promise to contact the Cache
Manager if the centrally stored copy of a file changes while the Cache Manager
has a cached copy.  If the central copy changes, the File Exporter revokes the
token; the Cache Manager sees that the token is revoked and retrieves the new
version of the file when an application program next requests data from it.
.iX "-]" "tokens" "about"
.H 3 "Cache Manager Processes"
.iX "\*Ldfsd\*O process" "about"
.P
The \*Ldfsd\*O process controls the Cache Manager, which runs in the kernel.
You can add options to the \*Vdcelocal\*L/bin/dfsd\*O command and modify
the \*Vdcelocal\*L/etc/CacheInfo\*O file on the client machine to customize
DFS cache parameters.
.P
You can control several Cache Manager features with \*Ldfsd\*O options. 
The \*Ldfsd\*O process must be invoked at or after system reboot on all 
DFS client machines; it is recommended that the \*Ldfsd\*O command be 
added to the proper initialization file (\*L/etc/rc\*O or its equivalent). 
The \*Ldfsbind\*O process must be run before the \*Ldfsd\*O process; it 
is recommended that the \*Vdcelocal\*L/bin/dfsbind\*O command also be added 
to the proper initialization file.
.H 3 "Cache Manager Files"
.iX "\*LCacheInfo\*O file"
.iX "Cache Manager" "local files"
.iX "V files" "editing and deleting"
.iX "\*LCacheItems\*O file" "editing and deleting"
.iX "\*LFilesetItems\*O file" "editing and deleting"
The \*LCacheInfo\*O file, which is manually created during DFS client 
installation, is composed of three fields separated by colons: the first 
field specifies where the DCE global namespace is mounted; the second field 
names the cache directory where the Cache Manager creates its cache files; 
and the third field specifies the cache size in 1024-byte (1-kilobyte) blocks.
.P
The Cache Manager creates and maintains the following files, which are not
intended for direct use.  You can cause the kernel to panic if you accidentally
modify any of these files; if this happens, rebooting the machine should
restore normal performance.  Note that these files exist only on client
machines that use disk caching; a machine that uses a memory cache maintains
in memory the cache information the files contain.
.nS "caution"
\*ENever\*O directly modify or delete these files; this can cause the kernel
to panic. \*EAlways\*O use the commands provided with DFS to alter these files.
.nE
.ML
.LI
Multiple \*Vdcelocal\*L/var/adm/dfs/cache/V\*Vn\*O files, where \*Vn\*O is a 
unique number for each file.  By default, each \*LV\*Vn\*O file holds up to 
64 kilobytes of a cached file; files larger than 64 kilobytes are divided 
into multiple files.  The number of \*LV\*Vn\*O files, or \*LV\*O files, 
depends on the cache size.
.LI
The \*Vdcelocal\*L/var/adm/dfs/cache/CacheItems\*O file.  The Cache Manager 
uses this binary file to record information about each \*LV\*O file, 
including its file ID number and data version number.
.LI
The \*Vdcelocal\*L/var/adm/dfs/cache/FilesetItems\*O file.  This binary file 
stores the fileset-to-mount point mapping for each fileset accessed.  This 
mapping enables the Cache Manager to respond correctly to commands such 
as \*Lpwd\*O.
.LE
.iX "-]" "Cache Manager" "about"
.H 2 "Cache Manager Features You Can Customize"
.iX "-[" "Cache Manager" "customizing"
.P
You can alter the following aspects of the Cache Manager configuration to
achieve different levels of performance on different client machines:
.ML
.LI
Disk or Memory Cache: You can direct the Cache Manager to use machine
memory instead of disk space for caching.
.LI
Chunk Size and Number: You can use several options with \*Ldfsd\*O to
alter the default size and number of chunks that compose a cache.  With a
disk cache, each chunk is called a \*LV\*O file; with a memory cache, each 
chunk is represented by a block of memory.  The size and number of chunks can 
be modified to take advantage of fast networks or to compensate for 
slow networks.
.LI
Cache Location: The standard location of the cache (which is at
\*Vdcelocal\*L/var/adm/dfs/cache\*O) can be changed to take advantage of
greater space availability on other partitions.
.LI
Cache Size: The cache size influences how often the Cache Manager
contacts File Server machines across the network.  Increasing the cache size
results in better performance because fewer cross-network calls are necessary.
.LI
.zA "enh,13566,R1.2.2,Add multihomed server"
File Server and FL Server Preferences: The Cache Manager maintains
entries that contain the machine specifications (either host names or
IP addresses) and preference ranks for File Servers and FL Servers. A
File Server entry's rank determines the Cache Manager's preference for
electing to access replicas at that address over replicas that are
available through other network connections. Similarly, an FL Server
entry's rank determines the Cache Manager's preference for querying
the FLDB through a particular address.  You can specify preferences
for both types of server machines to bias the Cache Manager's
selection process. A File Server or FL Server will normally have up to
four entries in a Cache Manager's preference list, with each entry having
a separate machine specification.
.zZ "enh,13566,R1.2.2,Add multihomed server"
.LI
The \*Lsetuid\*O Status: By default, the Cache Manager does not allow
\*Lsetuid\*O programs from filesets to execute with \*Lsetuid\*O permission.
You can enable \*Lsetuid\*O programs from specific filesets to execute with
\*Lsetuid\*O permission; \*Lsetgid\*O programs on a fileset are enabled and
disabled along with \*Lsetuid\*O programs.
.LI
Device File Status: By default, the Cache Manager does not honor device
files stored in filesets.  You can instruct the Cache Manager to recognize
device files from specific filesets.
.LI
Cached File Versions: The DFS token mechanism guarantees that the Cache
Manager uses the most current versions of files and directories.  You can also
force the Cache Manager to discard the versions you are using and fetch new
versions from the File Server machine.
.nL
.ne 20
.LI
Unstored Data: If the Cache Manager cannot contact a File Server machine
to write data to it, it keeps the unstored data in the cache.  It then continues
to attempt to contact the File Server machine until it can store the data.  You
can list all of the data the Cache Manager cannot store, and you can force 
the Cache Manager to discard the data rather than to continue to try to contact
unavailable File Server machines.
.zA "enh, 13605, R1.2.2, Security enhancements"
.LI
RPC Authentication Levels: The Cache Manager and File Server default authentication levels are such that communications default to the packet integrity RPC authentication level.  You can set two sets of initial RPC authentication levels and minimum RPC authentication levels; one set governs communications with File Servers in the local cell, while the second set governs communications with File Servers in foreign cells.
.zZ "enh, 13605, R1.2.2, Security enhancements"
.LE
.nS "note"
You must issue the commands described in this chapter at a console or terminal
of the machine being configured; you cannot specify a different machine name
to be used with these commands.  Some of the commands require that you log in
as \*Lroot\*O, while others require no privileges; the necessary privileges 
are indicated with each command.  All of the files mentioned in this chapter 
are local files.
.nE
.H 2 "Choosing Cache Type, Location, and Size"
.iX "caching" "types"
.iX "memory cache"
.iX "disk cache" "about"
.iX "\*LCacheInfo\*O file"
.P
The default DFS configuration is disk caching. However, the Cache Manager can
use a machine memory cache rather than a disk cache.  To direct the Cache
Manager to use memory caching, use the \*L\-memcache\*O option with the
\*Ldfsd\*O command.  When the \*L\-memcache\*O option is used, the Cache Manager
does no disk caching, even if the machine has a disk available.
.P
The \*LCacheInfo\*O file defines the directory to use for a disk cache and
the size of a disk or memory cache.  The Cache Manager checks this file at
initialization to determine this information.  The \*LCacheInfo\*O file
contains the following three fields separated by colons:
.ML
.LI
A directory on the local disk where the Cache Manager mounts the DCE global
namespace.  The default entry is the global namespace designation (\*L/...\*O).
If \*L/...\*O is not specified, symbolic links to the global namespace fail.
.nL
.ne 20
.LI
A local directory that serves as the DFS cache for a disk cache.  The Cache
Manager creates its cache files in this directory.  The default entry is
\*Vdcelocal\*L/var/adm/dfs/cache\*O.  Although the indicated directory is not
used with a memory cache, an entry \*Emust\*O appear in this field even 
if memory caching is employed on the machine.
.LI
A definition of the cache size in kilobyte blocks.
.LE
.P
Following is an example of a \*LCacheInfo\*O file. The file lists the DCE
namespace mounted at the global namespace designation (\*L/...\*O), the
\*Vdcelocal\*L/var/adm/dfs/cache\*O directory used for the cache, and a defined
cache size of 50,000 kilobyte blocks (the machine \*Emust\*O have this 
many blocks available on its disk):
.oS
\*C/...:\*Vdcelocal\*O\*C/var/adm/dfs/cache:50000\*O
.oE
.H 2 "Altering Default Parameters with the dfsd Process"
.iX "-[" "\*Ldfsd\*O process" "changing defaults"
.iX "-[" "cache" "changing size"
.iX "-[" "chunks" "about"
.P
.zA "enh, 13605, R1.2.2, Security enhancements"
The fields in the \*LCacheInfo\*O file are the only Cache Manager parameters
that you \*Emust\*O set.  However, you can use the options available with the
\*Ldfsd\*O command to alter several Cache Manager defaults, affecting the way
information is cached.  Following are the configuration parameters that have
the greatest effect on cache performance and security. (See the following subsections for a description of the \*Ldfsd\*O options used to configure these parameters.)
.ML
.LI
Total Cache Size: This is the amount of disk space or memory available
for caching.
.LI
Chunk Size: This parameter determines the maximum amount of data that
can fit in a cache chunk.  A chunk cannot hold more than one element; in a
memory cache, the unused memory that is allocated for a chunk is wasted.  If 
an element cannot fit in a single chunk, it is split into as many chunks 
as are needed.
.P
This parameter also determines the maximum amount of data that the Cache 
Manager can request at one time from a File Exporter.  Increase the chunk size 
to take advantage of very fast links or decrease the size for slow networks.
.nL
.ne 20
.LI
Cache Chunk Configuration: This parameter determines the number of
chunks that are used for the cache.  It can affect how often the Cache 
Manager must discard cached data to make room for new data.  Consider the 
following example:
.P
A disk cache is configured at 50 megabytes and consists of 1000 chunks.
Suppose 10 users each have the Cache Manager cache 100 files and each file is
20 kilobytes in size.  This uses all 1000 chunks available (because each chunk
can hold only one element), even though the cache has only 20 megabytes of
cached elements, which is less than 50% of its capacity of 50 megabytes.
.P
When a user requests more data, the Cache Manager must discard cached data to
reclaim space, even though the cache is not close to its capacity.  In this
case, increasing the number of chunks into which the cache is divided would
improve performance by allowing the unused 30 megabytes of cache capacity to
be allocated for other cached files.
.LI
Number of dcache (disk cache) Entries in Memory: The Cache Manager maintains
one dcache entry for each cache chunk; the entry records system
identification information such as the file ID and version number of the file
corresponding to the chunk.  On disk caching machines, each dcache entry is
stored in the \*LCacheItems\*O file, with a small number of entries (by
default, 100) duplicated in machine memory.  On memory caching machines, all
dcache entries are stored in memory; the number of entries is equal to the
number of chunks.
.zA "enh, 13605, R1.2.2, Security enhancements"
.LI
Minimum and Initial RPC Authentication Levels: The Cache Manager maintains an initial authentication level used as a starting point for authentication negotiations with File Servers and a minimum acceptable level for communications with File Servers.  There are two sets of these parameters: one set governs communications with File Servers in the local cell, and the other set governs communications with File Servers in foreign cells.
.zZ "enh, 13605, R1.2.2, Security enhancements"
.LE
.P
.nS "note"
The \*Ldfsd\*O command is normally placed in a machine's initialization file
(\*L/etc/rc\*O or its equivalent), not typed at the console.  The commands in
the following subsections are presented as examples of entries from
initialization files.
.nE
.H 3 "Disk Cache Configuration"
.iX "-[" "cache" "disk"
.iX "-[" "disk cache" "about"
.P
The number of kilobyte blocks allocated to the cache is defined in the third
field of the \*LCacheInfo\*O file.  You can use the \*L\-blocks\*O option to
override the number of cache blocks; the unit of measure associated with the
cache block size is always kilobytes.  The Cache Manager heuristically divides
the number of blocks by 8 to determine the number of cache chunks in a disk
cache.  The following example sets the number of disk blocks allocated for the
cache to 75,000 kilobyte blocks:
.oS
\*Cdfsd -blocks 75000\*O
.oE
.P
The default number of cache chunks in a disk cache is computed as the number of
cache blocks divided by 8; you can use the \*L\-files\*O option with a positive
integer not greater than 32,000 to override this default.  To use your cache
most effectively, issue the \*Ldu\*O command on the cache directory to
determine the number of cache blocks used; compare this number to the number
of blocks allocated to the cache.  If you are not using 90% of the cache,
increase the number of chunks (\*LV\*O files).  The following example sets the 
number of chunks to 2000:
.oS
\*Cdfsd -files 2000\*O
.oE
.P
.EQ
delim %%
.EN
The default chunk size for a disk cache is 64 kilobytes (%2 sup 16%); the unit
of measure associated with the chunk size is always bytes.  You can use the
\*L\-chunksize\*O option to override the default chunk size.  Provide an integer
between 13 and 18 to be used as an exponent of 2.  For example, a value of 15
sets the chunk size to 32 kilobytes (%2 sup 15%= 32,768); a value of 16 equals
the default for disk caches (%2 sup 16%= 64 kilobytes).  A value less than 13
or greater than 18 returns the chunk size to the default (as does a value of
16).  The following example sets the chunk size to 16 kilobytes (%2 sup 14%):
.EQ
delim off
.EN
.oS
\*Cdfsd -chunksize 14\*O
.oE
.P
For a disk cache, the default number of dcache entries duplicated in memory is
100.  You can use the \*L\-dcache\*O option with a positive integer to change
the default.  It is usually not necessary to duplicate more than 100 entries in
memory.  However, because memory access is faster than disk access, increasing
the number of dcache entries stored in memory may improve performance slightly.
The following example sets the number to 250:
.oS
\*Cdfsd -dcache 250\*O
.oE
.P
When altering a disk cache configuration, any combination of \*Ldfsd\*O options
is allowed.  However, the cache size defined in the \*LCacheInfo\*O file or
with the \*L\-blocks\*O option cannot be exceeded with the \*L\-files\*O or
\*L\-chunksize\*O option.
.iX "-]" "cache" "disk"
.iX "-]" "disk cache" "about"
.H 3 "Memory Cache Configuration"
.iX "-[" "cache" "memory" 
.iX "-[" "memory cache"
.P
.EQ
delim %%
.EN
The default chunk size for a memory cache is 8 kilobytes (%2 sup 13%).  There
is no predefined default for the number of chunks in a memory cache, and, as
mentioned previously, the number of dcache entries equals the number of chunks.
.EQ
delim off
.EN
.P
If the \*L\-blocks\*O option is used alone, it overrides the default cache size
in the \*LCacheInfo\*O file.  The Cache Manager divides this value by the
default chunk size of 8 kilobytes to calculate the number of chunks and dcache
entries.  The following example sets the cache size to 5 megabytes (5120
kilobytes); as a result, the number of chunks is set to 640 (5120 divided by
8):
.oS
\*Cdfsd -memcache -blocks 5120\*O
.oE
.P
.EQ
delim %%
.EN
If the \*L\-chunksize\*O option is used alone, it overrides the default of 8
kilobytes (%2 sup 13%).  Provide an integer between 13 and 18 to be used as an
exponent of 2.  For example, a value of 15 sets the chunk size to 32 kilobytes
(%2 sup 15%= 32,768).  A value less than 13 or greater than 18 returns the
chunk size to the default (as does a value of 13).  The following example sets
the chunk size to 16 kilobytes (%2 sup 14%); if the total cache size is 4
megabytes (%2 sup 12% kilobytes), the resulting number of chunks is 256:
.EQ
delim off
.EN
.oS
\*Cdfsd -memcache -chunksize 14\*O
.oE
.P
.EQ
delim %%
.EN
If the \*L\-blocks\*O and \*L\-chunksize\*O options are used together, they
override the defaults for the cache size and the chunk size.  The Cache Manager
divides the cache size by the chunk size to calculate the number of chunks
and dcache entries.  The following example sets the cache size to 8 
megabytes (8192 kilobytes) and the chunk size to 16 kilobytes (%2 sup 14%), 
resulting in 512 chunks:
.EQ
delim off
.EN
.oS
\*Cdfsd -memcache -blocks 8192 -chunksize 14\*O
.oE
.P
.P
When configuring a memory cache, the following options explicitly set the
number of chunks and dcache entries.  They also set the cache size indirectly
and should not be used; use \*L\-blocks\*O, \*L\-chunksize\*O, or both, and allow
the Cache Manager to determine the number of chunks and dcache entries itself.
.ML
.LI
The \*L\-dcache\*O option alone.  The Cache Manager multiplies this value by
the default chunk size (8 kilobytes) to derive a total cache size, overriding
the value in the \*LCacheInfo\*O file.
.LI
A combination of \*L\-dcache\*O and \*L\-chunksize\*O options.  The Cache Manager 
sets the specified values and multiplies them together to obtain a total cache
size, again overriding the value in the \*LCacheInfo\*O file.
.LE
.P
Do not use the following options when configuring a memory cache:
.ML
.LI
The \*L\-files\*O option alone.  This option sets the number of chunks for a
disk cache and is thus ignored for a memory cache.
.LI
The \*L\-blocks\*O and \*L\-dcache\*O options together.  If you combine these
options, the Cache Manager may choose one of the values to ignore, or the
command may fail.
.LE
.P
(See Part 2 of this guide and reference for complete information about these
options and the use of the \*Ldfsd\*O command in general.)
.iX "-]" "chunks" "about"
.H 2 "Changing Cache Location"
.iX "-[" "cache" "changing location"
.P
The default directory for the Cache Manager's cache is
\*Vdcelocal\*L/var/adm/dfs/cache\*O.  You can change this to a directory on
another partition if more space is available.  Use the \*Ldu\*O or \*Ldf\*O
command (or an equivalent command) to check partition size and fullness.
.P
You can change the location of the cache by editing the \*LCacheInfo\*O file
or by using the \*L\-cachedir\*O option with the \*Ldfsd\*O command. (See Part
2 of this guide and reference for more information about the use of the
\*Ldfsd\*O command.)
.P
To change the cache location, do the following:
.AL
.LI
Log in as \*Lroot\*O on the machine.
.LI
Use a text editor to change the second field of the \*LCacheInfo\*O file (the
information between the two colons).  The new directory must be on the local
disk of the machine.  The following example shows the cache directory specified
in the \*LCacheInfo\*O file changed to \*L/usr/cache\*O:
.oS
\*C/...:/usr/cache:15000\*O
.oE
.P
.LI
Reboot the machine using \*L/etc/reboot\*O or its equivalent. (Consult your
system documentation for information on the correct rebooting command for your
workstation.)
.LI
Move to the old cache directory and delete it using the \*Lrm -rf\*O command.
.LE
.iX "-]" "cache" "changing location"
.H 2 "Listing and Setting Cache Size"
.iX "cache" "calculating size"
.P
The amount of local disk space or memory allocated for the Cache Manager to
use for its cache affects the speed of file access.  A larger cache means the
Cache Manager has to contact the File Server machine less often, resulting in
fewer cross-network messages.  A smaller cache fills sooner, making it more
likely that the Cache Manager must discard cached copies of data to make room
for newly requested data; if the user requests the discarded data again, the
Cache Manager must recontact the File Server machine and refetch the data.  A
larger cache can make the initial discarding of data unnecessary.
.P
The amount of disk space or memory used for caching depends on several factors.
The size of the partition that houses the cache directory or the amount of
memory available on the machine places an absolute limit on cache size.  Do not
use more than 90% of the cache directory's partition for a disk cache; do not
use more than 20 to 25% of available memory for a memory cache (this leaves
enough memory for processes and applications to run).
.P
Within these limits, devoting more than 40 megabytes to the cache on a machine
that does not serve multiple users is normally not useful unless users often
work with large amounts of data (accessing large databases, for example).  If a
machine serves multiple users, a cache of 60 to 70 megabytes may be
appropriate.  A cache smaller than 5 megabytes can hamper Cache Manager
performance; a cache smaller than twice the chunk size is rounded up.
.nL
.ne 20
.P
.iX "-[" "\*LCacheInfo\*O file" 
You can reset the cache size for both types of caches by using a text editor
to alter the size field in the \*LCacheInfo\*O file and then rebooting the
machine; you must be logged in as \*Lroot\*O or have the write permission
on the file to edit it.  The \*L\-blocks\*O option can also be used with the
\*Ldfsd\*O command to override the \*LCacheInfo\*O value at reboot. (See Part
2 of this guide and reference for complete information about the \*Ldfsd\*O
command.)
.P
To alter disk cache size without rebooting the machine, use the \*Lcm
setcachesize\*O command.  The value remains in effect until the machine is
next rebooted and reads the value in the \*LCacheInfo\*O file.  To display the
current cache size, the amount being used, and the type of cache (disk or
memory), use the \*Lcm getcachesize\*O command.
.P
You must reboot to reset the cache size for a memory-caching machine.
.iX "-]" "\*Ldfsd\*O process" "changing defaults" 
.iX "-]" "cache" "memory"
.iX "-]" "memory cache"
.H 3 "Displaying the Cache Size from the CacheInfo File"
.iX "cache" "viewing size"
.P
Use the \*Lcat\*O command (or the command appropriate to your system) to view
the \*LCacheInfo\*O file on a client machine:
.iS
\*C$ \*Lcat CacheInfo\*O
.iE
.P
The \*LCacheInfo\*O file contains a single line that lists three fields 
separated by a colon; the third field lists the maximum number of kilobyte 
blocks the Cache Manager can reserve for use as a cache in the designated 
cache directory.
.P
In the following example, the default cache size for the machine is 25,000
kilobyte blocks:
.iS
\*C$ \*Lcat CacheInfo\*O
.iE
.P
.oS
\*C/...:\*Vdcelocal\*O\*C/var/adm/dfs/cache:25000\*O
.oE
.nL
.ne 20
.H 3 "Displaying the Current Cache Size and the Amount in Use"
.iX "\*Lcm\*O command suite" "\*Lgetcachesize\*O"
.P
Issue the \*Lcm getcachesize\*O command on a client machine to view the
current size of the cache and the amount in use.  On machines that use disk
caching, the current cache size may disagree with the default size specified
in the \*LCacheInfo\*O file if the cache size was changed with the \*Lcm
setcachesize\*O command.  Regardless of the type of caching in use, the current
cache size may also disagree with the \*LCacheInfo\*O file if the size was
changed with the \*L\-blocks\*O option of the \*Ldfsd\*O command.
.iS
\*C$ \*Lcm getcachesize\*O
.iE
.P
The following example shows the number of kilobyte blocks that the Cache 
Manager is using as a cache at the moment the command is issued and the 
current size of the cache:
.iS
\*C$ \*Lcm getcachesize\*O
.iE
.P
.oS
\*CUsing 13709 of the cache's available 25000 1K byte blocks.\*O
.oE
.H 3 "Changing the Cache Size Temporarily"
.P
You can reset the cache size without rebooting a machine. The value remains
in effect until you next reboot the machine.  To change the cache size
temporarily, do the following:
.AL
.LI
Log in as \*Lroot\*O on the machine.
.LI
Issue the \*Lcm setcachesize\*O command to set a new cache size:
.iS
\*C# \*Lcm setcachesize -size \*Vkilobytes\*O
.iE
.P
The \*L\-size\*O \*Vkilobytes\*O option is the number of kilobyte blocks to 
be used for the cache.  A value of 1024 equals 1 megabyte; the smallest 
allowable value is 1.  A value less than 5120 (5 megabytes) can have a 
negative effect on Cache Manager performance; a value less than twice the 
chunk size is rounded up.  A value of 0 (zero) resets the cache size to 
the amount specified in the \*LCacheInfo\*O file.
.LE
.H 3 "Resetting the Cache Size to the Default"
.P
To reset the cache size to the default, do the following:
.AL
.LI
Log in as \*Lroot\*O on the machine.
.LI
Use the \*L\-reset\*O option with the \*Lcm setcachesize\*O command to reset
the cache size to the value specified at the last reboot, which is either the
value in the \*LCacheInfo\*O file or the value set with the \*L\-blocks\*O
option of the \*Ldfsd\*O command:
.iS
\*C# \*Lcm setcachesize -reset\*O
.iE
.P
The \*L\-reset\*O option resets the cache size to the value at the last reboot.
.LE
.H 3 "Changing the Cache Size Permanently"
.P
To change the cache size permanently, do the following:
.AL
.LI
Log in as \*Lroot\*O on the machine.
.LI
Use a text editor to change the number in the third field of the
\*LCacheInfo\*O file.  Specify a number in kilobyte blocks; 1024 kilobyte blocks
equals 1 megabyte.  Following is an example of the \*LCacheInfo\*O file:
.oS
\*C/...:\*Vdcelocal\*O\*C/var/adm/dfs/cache:25000\*O
.oE
.P
.nS "caution"
Be precise when editing the \*LCacheInfo\*O file.  Use colons to
separate the fields in the file; do not include any spaces in the
file.
.nE
.LI
Reboot using \*L/etc/reboot\*O or its equivalent. (Consult your system
documentation for information on the correct rebooting command for your
workstation.)
.LE
.iX "-]" "cache" "changing size"
.iX "-]" "\*LCacheInfo\*O file"
.H 2 "Setting File Server and Fileset Location Server Machine Preferences"
.iX "-[" "Cache Manager" "setting File Server preferences"
.iX "-[" "Cache Manager" "checking File Server preferences"
.iX "-[" "Cache Manager" "setting FL Server preferences"
.iX "-[" "Cache Manager" "checking FL Server preferences"
.iX "-[" "File Server machines" "setting Cache Manager preferences"
.iX "-[" "FL Server machines" "setting Cache Manager preferences"
.iX "-[" "File Server machines" "checking Cache Manager preferences"
.iX "-[" "FL Server machines" "checking Cache Manager preferences"
.P
A replicated DCE LFS fileset typically has multiple read-only replicas. Each
replica provides the same data, but each resides on a different File Server.
When the Cache Manager needs to access data from a read-only replica, the FL
Server provides the Cache Manager with the names of all File Servers
on which that replica resides. As with File Servers, there can be multiple
FL servers. The Cache Manager must choose the FL server to query for
fileset locations and then choose the Fileset Server to access.
.P
To choose from among these servers, the Cache Manager consults its
collection of File Server and FL server preferences. Each preference
consists of the hostname or Internet Protocol (IP) address of a server and
the machine's numerical rank in the range from 1 to 65,534. The Cache
Manager attempts to access the server that has the lowest recorded rank. If
two FL servers have the same rank, the Cache Manager selects them in the
order in which their names appear in the file system junction. If two File
Servers have the same rank, the Cache Manager selects them in the order in
which it received their names from the FL Server.
.P
If the Cache Manager cannot access the server with the lowest rank\(embecause
the machine is currently unavailable, for example\(emit attempts to access
the server with the next-lowest rank. It continues in this fashion until it
either succeeds or determines that all File Servers or FL Servers are
unavailable.
.P
The Cache Manager stores its server preferences in the kernel of the local
machine. Therefore, it loses its current preferences each time it is
initialized. To rebuild its preferences following initialization, the Cache
Manager assigns a default rank to each File Server or FL Server that it
contacts.  The Cache Manager bases its default ranks on IP addresses, as
follows:
.ML
.LI
If the local machine is also a File Server or FL Server, it receives an
initial rank of 5000.
.LI
Each File Server or FL Server in the same subnetwork as the local machine receives
an initial rank of 20,000.
.LI
Each File Server or FL Server in the same network as the local machine
receives an initial rank of 30,000.
.LI
Each File Server or FL Server in a different network from the local machine, or
for which the Cache Manager can determine no network information, receives an
initial rank of 40,000.
.LE
.P
.zA "enh,13566,R1.2.2,Add multihomed server"
When multiple server entries have the same rank, the Cache Manager
chooses between connections to suitable servers by picking the machine
with the lowest "round-trip time." When initialized, the Cache Manager
assigns a randomly adjusted round-trip time value to each server entry
in the preference list. The assigned round-trip time value is always
greater than the limit for recorded values for actual round-trip
times, thus biasing the selection process to any connection that the Cache
Manager has actually made.  The assigned round-trip time value ensures
that if more than one entry have the same rank (a very probable event
given the default values assigned to entries) then no single entry
will receive all requests from the various DFS clients.
.P
To display the Cache Manager's current set of File Server connection
preferences, use the \*Lcm getpreferences\*O command. Use the \*Lcm
getpreferences\*O command with the \*L\-fldb\*O option to display the
current set of FL Server connection preferences. By default, the
command displays its output on standard output, but you can direct the
output to a specified file. Note that each server will normally have
up to four entries, each with a different IP address.
.P
To specify preferences for one or more File Server connections, use
the \*Lcm setpreferences\*O command. Use the \*Lcm setpreferences\*O
command with the \*L-fldb\*O option to specify preferences for one or
more FL Server connections.  Each preference entry that you specify
must consist of the following pair of values: the machine
specification (either the host name or IP address of the File Server or
FL Server) and that machine's rank in the form of an integer in the
range from 1 to 65,534 (lower ranks have a higher preference). You can
specify up to four preference entries for the same server, with each
entry using a different IP address.
.P
Use the command's options to specify File Server or FL Server preference
entries as follows:
.ML
.LI
Use the \*L-server\*O option to specify one or more File Server entries 
on the command line. If the \*L\-fldb\*O option is not used, the
\*L-server\*O option specifies File Server machine specifications 
and their ranks. 
For
example, the following command assigns the File Server host names
\*Lfs1.abc.com\*O and \*Lfs2.abc.com\*O ranks of 19,000 and 21,000,
respectively:
.iS
\*C# \*Lcm setp -se fs1.abc.com 19000 fs2.abc.com 21000\*O
.iE
.LI
Use the \*L-fldb\*O option with the \*L-server\*O option to
set one or more FL Server preference entries.  For example, the
following command assigns the FL Server host names \*Lfl1.abc.com\*O and
\*Lfl2.abc.com\*O with ranks of 15,000 and 25,000, respectively:
.iS
\*C# \*Lcm setp -se fl1.abc.com 15000 fl2.abc.com 25000 -fldb\*O
.iE
.LI
Use the \*L-path\*O option to specify the pathname of a file that 
contains
server preferences. (The output from the \*Lcm getpreferences\*O
command can be redirected to create such a file.) For example, 
the following
command reads a collection of preferences from a file that resides on the
local machine at
\*L/etc/cm.prefs\*O:
.iS
\*C# \*Lcm setp -pa /etc/cm.prefs\*O
.iE
.P
The preference file should contain lines similar to the following:
.oS
\*C121.86.33.41 39000
121.86.33.34 39000
121.86.33.36 41000
121.86.33.37 41000\*O
.oE
.LI
Use the \*L-stdin\*O option to read preference entries 
from standard input. 
For example, the following command reads preferences piped to the command 
from a user-defined program named
\*Lmkprefs\*O:
.iS
\*C# \*Lmkprefs | cm setp -st\*O
.iE
.P
The program should generate preferences in the following format:
.oS
\*Cfs3.abc.com 15000 fs4.abc.com 25000 ...\*O
.oE
.LE
.P
The \*L-server\*O, \*L-path\*O, and \*L-stdin\*O options are not
mutually exclusive. You can include any combination of the options
with the \*Lcm setpreferences\*O command. If the Cache Manager already
has a rank for a File Server or FL Server connection 
that you specify, the rank
you specify replaces the connection's existing rank.
.P
Each Cache Manager maintains its own collection of preferences, so 
two Cache
Managers can have two different ranks for the same File Server or 
FL Server connection.
.P
To load a predefined set of preferences each time the Cache Manager
is initialized, include the \*Lcm setpreferences\*O command in the 
machine's
initialization file.
.H 3 "Displaying File Server and FL Server Preferences"
.iX "\*Lcm\*O command suite" "\*Lgetpreferences\*O"
.P
Issue the \*Lcm getpreferences\*O command to display the Cache Manager's
preferences for File Servers or FL Server connections, as follows:
.iS
\*C$ \*Lcm getpreferences\*O [\*L\-path \*Vfilename\*O] [\*L\-numeric\*O] [\*L\-fldb\*O]
.iE
.P
The \*L\-path \*Vfilename\*O option specifies a file to which the 
command is
to write its output. Omit this option to display the preferences 
on standard 
output.
.P
The \*L\-numeric\*O option directs the command to display the IP addresses
rather than the host names of the server machine connections. 
Omit this option to display the host names.
.P
The \*L\-fldb\*O option directs the command to display the 
FL Server machine connections
and their respective ranks and not File Servers.
.P
The command produces output of the following form for each server 
connection preference:
.oS
\*Vhostname\*C          \*Vrank\*O
.oE
.P
For example:
.oS
\*Lfl2.abc.com\*O             \*L25000\*O
.oE
.P
In the output, \*Vhostname\*O is the host name of a File or FL Server, and
\*Vrank\*O is the machine's numeric preference rank. 
Note that \*Vhostname\*O is 
replaced with the machine's IP address if the Cache
Manager cannot presently determine the host name or if the \*L-numeric\*O
option is included with the command.
.H 3 "Setting File Server Preferences"
.iX "\*Lcm\*O command suite" "\*Lsetpreferences\*O"
.P
To set the Cache Manager's preferences for one or more File Server or
FL Server
connections,
do the following:
.AL
.LI
Log in as \*Lroot\*O on the machine.
.LI
Issue the \*Lcm setpreferences\*O command to set the Cache Manager's
preferences for one or more File Server or FL Server connections, 
as follows:
.iS
\*C# \*Lcm setpreferences\*O [\*L\-server \*Vmachine rank\*O...] [\*L\-path \*Vfilename\*O] [\*L\-stdin\*O] [\*L\-fldb\*O]
.iE
.P
.zA "enh,13566,R1.2.2,Add multihomed server"
The \*L\-server \*Vmachine rank\*O option specifies one or more pairs of
server machine specifications 
(either through the host names or IP addresses) 
and their ranks.  By default, the machines are considered to
be File Servers; however, you can specify FL Server entries by adding the 
\*L\-fldb\*O option. Separate each machine specification and each
rank with one or more spaces. Note that you can specify up to four
entries per server, with each entry having a separate machine 
specification.
.zZ "enh,13566,R1.2.2,Add multihomed server"
.P
The \*L\-path \*Vfilename\*O option specifies a file from which 
the command is
to read one or more pairs of File Server specifications and their ranks. 
Separate
each machine specification from its rank with one or more spaces, and 
include
each paired machine specification and rank on a separate line.
.P
The \*L\-stdin\*O option directs the command to read pairs of File Server
specifications
and their ranks from standard input. Separate each machine 
specification and
each rank with one or more spaces.
.P
The \*L\-fldb\*O option directs the command to set preferences for 
FL Server addresses, 
rather than for File Servers. 
.LE
.zZ "enh,13566,R1.2.2,Add multihomed server"
