.H 2 "Determining setuid Permission"
.iX "-[" "permissions" "\*Lsetuid\*O"
.iX "-[" "\*Lsetuid\*O permission"
.P
Programs that have \*Lsetuid\*O permission allow users to perform operations 
and access local files for which they normally may not have the necessary
permissions.  Such a program allows anyone who uses it to execute with the
permissions of the user who owns the program for the duration of the program's
execution.
.P
While a \*Lsetuid\*O program executes, the person executing it is treated as 
the owner of the program.  The effective user identification number (UID) of
the executing program is the UID of the person who owns the program, not the
UID of the person who initiated the program's execution.  Thus, the person
executing the program is granted the same permissions as the person who owns
the program for as long as the program executes.
.P
A \*Lsetuid\*O program owned by \*Lroot\*O allows a user who executes the
program to execute with \*Lroot\*O privilege for the duration of the program.
When handled correctly, such \*Lsetuid\*O programs are very useful.  For
example, programs that modify the password file for a system (\*L/etc/passwd\*O
or its equivalent) are \*Lsetuid\*O programs that allow users to execute with
\*Lroot\*O privilege long enough to modify their passwords.  When handled
incorrectly, however, \*Lsetuid\*O programs owned by \*Lroot\*O can present
a serious breach in security.
.P
In the UNIX operating system, \*Lsetuid\*O programs are indicated by setting
a mode bit associated with a file.  By default, the Cache Manager does not
allow \*Lsetuid\*O programs to execute with \*Lsetuid\*O permission.  Use the
\*Lcm setsetuid\*O command to enable \*Lsetuid\*O programs from specific
filesets to execute with \*Lsetuid\*O permission.  The command sets \*Lsetuid\*O
status on a per-fileset and per-Cache Manager basis.  It is commonly included in
a start-up file (\*L/etc/rc\*O or its equivalent) to enable \*Lsetuid\*O 
programs from a specified fileset at machine startup.
.P
Note that \*Lsetuid\*O programs are effective only in the local environment.
A \*Lsetuid\*O program can change only the local identity under which a program
runs; it cannot change the DCE identity with which a program executes because
it provides no Kerberos tickets.  DCE does not recognize the change to the local
identity associated with a \*Lsetuid\*O program.
.P
Use the \*Lcm getsetuid\*O command to determine whether the Cache Manager
allows programs from specific filesets to execute with \*Lsetuid\*O permission.
.nL
.ne 20
.nS "note"
Every program also has a \*Lsetgid\*O bit that, when set, allows a person
executing the program to execute with the permissions of the group that owns 
the program for the duration of its execution.  When the \*Lcm setsetuid\*O 
command is used, it automatically enables or disables \*Lsetgid\*O permission 
at the same time.  Thus, if \*Lsetuid\*O programs are enabled on a fileset,
\*Lsetgid\*O programs are also enabled on that same fileset.
.nE
.H 3 "Checking setuid Permission"
.iX "\*Lcm\*O command suite" "\*Lgetsetuid\*O"
.P
Issue the \*Lcm getsetuid\*O command to determine the status of \*Lsetuid\*O
programs on specific filesets:
.iS
\*C$ \*Lcm getsetuid \*O[\*L\-path\*O {\*Vfilename\*O | \*Vdirectory_name\*O}...]
.iE
.P
The \*L\-path\*O option specifies a file or directory from each fileset 
whose \*Lsetuid\*O status is to be displayed.  Omit this option to display the 
status for the fileset that contains the current working directory.
.P
The output from this command includes a line for each specified fileset,
stating one of the following:
.ML
.LI
\*Cno setuid allowed\*O
.P
Indicates that \*Lsetuid\*O (and \*Lsetgid\*O) programs from the fileset are
disabled
.LI
\*Csetuid allowed\*O
.P
Indicates that \*Lsetuid\*O (and \*Lsetgid\*O) programs from the fileset are
enabled
.LI
\*Ccm: the fileset on which `\*O\*Vpathname\*O\*C' resides does not exist\*O
.P
Indicates that the pathname specified with the \*L\-path\*O option is invalid
.LE
.nL
.ne 20
.H 3 "Changing setuid Permission"
.iX "\*Lcm\*O command suite" "\*Lsetsetuid\*O"
.iX "\*Lsetgid\*O bit"
.P
To change \*Lsetuid\*O permission, do the following:
.AL
.LI
Log in as \*Lroot\*O on the machine.
.LI
Issue the \*Lcm setsetuid\*O command to change the status of \*Lsetuid\*O (and
\*Lsetgid\*O) programs on specific filesets:
.iS
\*C# \*Lcm setsetuid \*O[\*L\-path\*O {\*Vfilename\*O | \*Vdirectory_name\*O}...] [\*L\-state\*O {\*Lon\*O |\*L off\*O}]
.iE
.P
The \*L\-path\*O option specifies a file or directory from each fileset 
whose \*Lsetuid\*O status is to be changed.  Omit this option to change the 
status for the fileset that contains the current working directory.
.P
The \*L\-state on\*O option allows \*Lsetuid\*O programs from the indicated 
filesets to execute with \*Lsetuid\*O permission; the \*L\-state off\*O option
prevents \*Lsetuid\*O programs from the indicated filesets from executing 
with \*Lsetuid\*O permission.  If this option is omitted, \*Lsetuid\*O 
programs from the specified filesets are allowed to execute with \*Lsetuid\*O 
permission.
.LE
.iX "-]" "permissions" "\*Lsetuid\*O"
.iX "-]" "\*Lsetuid\*O permission" 
.H 2 "Determining Device File Status"
.iX "-[" "Cache Manager" "device file status"
.iX "-[" "device files" "determining status"
...\".iX "diskless machines" "device files"
...\".iX "machines" "diskless"
.P
In UNIX file systems, devices are represented as special device files.  By
convention, device files reside in the \*L/dev\*O directory or a subdirectory
of that directory; the UNIX kernel always honors device files stored in the
\*L/dev\*O directory.  However, the Cache Manager determines whether device
files stored in filesets in the global namespace are honored.  By default, the
Cache Manager does not honor device files stored in filesets in the global
namespace.
.P
You can use the \*Lcm setdevok\*O command to instruct the Cache Manager to
honor device files stored on specific filesets.  The command sets device file
status on a per-fileset and per-Cache Manager basis.  It is commonly included
in a start-up file (\*L/etc/rc\*O or its equivalent) to honor device files at
machine startup.
...\" .cS
...\" This is especially useful for diskless machines.  Because the \*L/dev\*O
...\" directory cannot be a local directory, the Cache Manager must be instructed
...\" to honor device files stored in filesets used by diskless machines.
...\" .cE
.P
Use the \*Lcm getdevok\*O command to determine whether the Cache Manager honors
device files from specific filesets.
.H 3 "Checking Device File Status"
.iX "\*Lcm\*O command suite" "\*Lgetdevok\*O"
.P
Issue the \*Lcm getdevok\*O command to determine whether the Cache Manager
honors device files on specific filesets:
.iS
\*C$ \*Lcm getdevok \*O[\*L\-path\*O {\*Vfilename\*O | \*Vdirectory_name\*O}...]
.iE
.P
The \*L\-path\*O option specifies a file or directory from each fileset about 
which device file status information is to be displayed.  Omit this option 
to display the status for the fileset containing the current working directory.
.P
The output from this command includes one line for each specified fileset,
stating one of the following:
.ML
.LI
\*Cdevice files allowed\*O
.P
Indicates that device files from the fileset are honored
.LI
\*Cdevice files not allowed\*O
.P
Indicates that device files from the fileset are not honored
.LI
\*Ccm: the fileset on which `\*O\*Vpathname\*O\*C' resides does not exist\*O
.P
Indicates that the pathname specified with the \*L\-path\*O option is invalid
.LE
.H 3 "Changing Device File Status"
.iX "\*Lcm\*O command suite" "\*Lsetdevok\*O"
.P
To change device file status, do the following:
.AL
.LI
Log in as \*Lroot\*O on the machine.
.LI
Issue the \*Lcm setdevok\*O command to change the status of device files on
specific filesets:
.iS
\*C# \*Lcm setdevok \*O[\*L\-path\*O {\*Vfilename\*O | \*Vdirectory_name\*O}...] [\*L\-state\*O {\*Lon\*O | \*Loff\*O}]
.iE
.P
The \*L\-path\*O option specifies a file or directory from each fileset for 
which device file status is to be changed.  Omit this option to change the 
status for the fileset containing the current working directory.
.P
The \*L\-state on\*O option causes device files from the indicated filesets to 
be honored; the \*L\-state off\*O option prevents device files from the 
indicated filesets from being honored.  If this option is omitted, device 
files from the specified filesets are honored.
.LE
.iX "-]" "Cache Manager" "device file status"
.iX "-]" "device files" "determining status"
.H 2 "Updating Cached Data"
.iX "-[" "cache" "updating"
.iX "cache" "criteria for updating"
.P
When an application program requests new data and the cache is full, the Cache
Manager discards some data to make room for the new information.  It discards
databased on the following two factors:
.ML
.LI
If the data is reproducible; information is considered reproducible if it is
unchanged from its first retrieval.  By definition, data from read-only filesets
is always reproducible; data from read/write filesets that was changed by a 
local application is considered reproducible if the changes are stored to 
the File Server machine.
.LI
When the application program last referenced the data; data not used for the
longest time is discarded first.
.LE
.P
Thus, reproducible data not used for the longest time is discarded first. The
Cache Manager continues to discard Least Recently Used (LRU) data in this
fashion until there is enough room for the new data.
.P
You can force the Cache Manager to discard, or flush, data cached from files,
directories, and filesets.  You can flush individual files or directories with
the \*Lcm flush\*O command, or you can flush one or more filesets with the
\*Lcm flushfileset\*O command.  Flushing is necessary only in the event of file
system problems or for testing purposes.  The \*Lcm flush\*O and \*Lcm
flushfileset\*O commands do not cause the Cache Manager to discard changes to
data not written back to the central copies of files.  These commands also do 
not affect data in the buffers of application programs.
.P
The Cache Manager checks once an hour for changes that do not involve tokens, 
such as the release of a new version of a cached read-only fileset or a name 
change for any cached fileset.  You can force the Cache Manager to notice 
these changes at other times with the \*Lcm checkfilesets\*O command, which 
directs the Cache Manager to revise its table of mappings between fileset 
names and fileset ID numbers.
.H 3 "Flushing Specific Files or Directories"
.iX "\*Lcm\*O command suite" "\*Lflush\*O"
.iX "-[" "cache" "flushing"
.P
Issue the \*Lcm flush\*O command to discard data from specific files or
directories:
.iS
\*C$ \*Lcm flush \*O[\*L\-path\*O {\*Vfilename\*O | \*Vdirectory_name\*O}...]
.iE
.P
The \*L\-path\*O option names each file or directory that you want to flush 
from the cache.  If a \*Vdirectory_name\*O is used, the Cache Manager flushes 
the name mappings and the blocks associated only with the directory, not with
the files in the directory.  If this option is omitted, the current working 
directory is flushed.
.H 3 "Flushing All Data from Specific Filesets"
.iX "\*Lcm\*O command suite" "\*Lflushfileset\*O"
.P
Issue the \*Lcm flushfileset\*O command to discard data from specific filesets:
.iS
\*C$ \*Lcm flushfileset \*O[\*L\-path\*O {\*Vfilename\*O | \*Vdirectory_name\*O}...]
.iE
.P
The \*L\-path\*O option names each file or directory in a fileset whose 
contents you want to flush.  The Cache Manager flushes everything cached from 
each fileset that contains a specified file or directory.  If this option 
is omitted, the fileset that contains the current working directory is flushed.
.H 3 "Forcing the Cache Manager to Notice Other Fileset Changes"
.P
Issue the \*Lcm checkfilesets\*O command to make the Cache Manager check for
changes to information about filesets that contain cached data:
.iS
\*C$ \*Lcm checkfilesets\*O
.iE
.P
.iX "-]" "cache" "flushing"
.H 2 "Discarding Unstored Data"
.iX "-[" "Cache Manager" "discarding data"
.P
The Cache Manager may occasionally be unable to write cached data back to a
File Server machine, possibly because the File Server machine is down or
because network problems prevent the Cache Manager from reaching it.  In this
event, the Cache Manager displays a message on the screen to notify the user
that it cannot write the data to the File Server machine.  If possible, it also
returns a failure code to the application program that is using the data.
.P
The Cache Manager keeps the unstored data in the cache and continues to attempt to contact the File Server machine until it can store the data. (The frequency with which the Cache Manager attempts to reach a File Server machine is 
defined with the \*L\-pollinterval\*O option of the \*Lfxd\*O command issued 
on that File Server machine.) In the meantime, corrective measures can be 
taken to alleviate the problem that prevents the data from being stored; for 
example, the File Server machine can be restarted.  Once the problem is 
alleviated, the Cache Manager can contact the File Server machine and store 
the data.
.P
The Cache Manager discards unstored data only when
.ML
.LI
It needs to make room in the cache for other data.  Given an average-sized cache
with average usage, the Cache Manager rarely needs to discard unstored data.
.LI
The \*Lcm resetstores\*O command is issued to force the Cache Manager to 
discard unstored data from the cache.  This command cancels the Cache 
Manager's continued attempts to contact unavailable File Server machines; 
\*Eall\*O data that the Cache Manager cannot store to such File Server machines
is discarded; you cannot selectively discard individual files or data from 
specific filesets.
.LE
.P
The \*Lcm resetstores\*O command affects only data that could not be written
to a File Server machine; it does not affect other data in the cache.
Nonetheless, issue the command only after issuing the \*Lcm lsstores\*O
command.  The \*Lcm lsstores\*O command lists the fileset ID numbers of
filesets that contain data that the Cache Manager cannot write to a File Server
machine.  Examine the output of the command to be sure that you know from
which filesets unstored data will be discarded.  You may be able to use this
information to ensure that unstored data from the indicated filesets can
safely be discarded.
.nS "note"
Because unstored data discarded from the cache cannot be recovered, any
problem that prevents data from being written to a File Server machine should
be handled promptly.
.nE
.P
.zA "enh,13566,R1.2.2,Add multihomed server"
You can use the \*Lcm statservers\*O command to determine which File Server
machines are failing to respond to the Cache Manager. (See Section 8.12 for
information about the \*Lcm statservers\*O command.)
.zZ "enh,13566,R1.2.2,Add multihomed server"
.H 3 "Listing Unstored Data"
.iX "\*Lcm\*O command suite" "\*Llsstores\*O"
.P
Issue the \*Lcm lsstores\*O command to list filesets that contain unstored data
that the Cache Manager cannot write back to a File Server machine:
.iS
\*C$ \*Lcm lsstores\*O
.iE
.H 3 "Discarding Unstored Data"
.iX "\*Lcm\*O command suite" "\*Lresetstores\*O"
.P
To discard unstored data, do the following:
.AL
.LI
Log in as \*Lroot\*O on the machine.
.LI
Issue the \*Lcm resetstores\*O command to cancel any further attempts by the
Cache Manager to contact unavailable File Server machines.  The Cache Manager
discards all data that it has been unable to store to such File Server
machines.
.iS
\*C# \*Lcm resetstores\*O
.iE
.LE
.iX "-]" "cache" "updating"
.iX "-]" "Cache Manager" "discarding data"
.iX "-]" "Cache Manager" "customizing"
.iX "-]" "client machines" "requirements"
.iX "-]" "Cache Manager" "configuring"
.H 2 "Checking File Server Machine Status"
.iX "-[" "Cache Manager" "checking File Server status"
.iX "-[" "File Server machines" "checking status"
.P
If the Cache Manager cannot access files or save files that it currently has
cached, you can use the \*Lcm statservers\*O command to determine if one or
more File Server machines are currently inaccessible.  The command checks the
status of each File Server machine with which the Cache Manager has been in
contact.  The command does not report the reason that a File Server machine
is unavailable, but it does list the names of unresponsive machines.
.P
The Cache Manager classifies as unresponsive any File Server machine that
meets the following pair of conditions:
.ML
.LI
The Cache Manager has been in contact with the File Exporter running on the
machine and needs to contact it in the future (for example, the Cache Manager
is holding tokens to data on the machine).
.LI
The File Exporter on the machine is not responding to the Cache Manager's
periodic probes (implying that it also is not responding to requests for data).
.LE
.P
The Cache Manager does not probe all File Server machines in the local cell;
it probes only those File Server machines that house data it has cached.
Similarly, the \*Lcm statservers\*O command is concerned only with File Server
machines that do not respond to the Cache Manager's probes.  You can use the
command to check the statuses of File Server machines that meet the first of
the previous two conditions and reside in the local cell, in a specific foreign
cell, or in any cell.
.P
.iX "\*Lcm\*O command suite" "\*Lstatservers\*O"
To check the status of each File Server machine with which the Cache Manager
has been in contact, issue the \*Lcm statservers\*O command:
.iS
\*C$ \*Lcm statservers \*O[{\*L-cell \*Vcellname\*O | \*L-all\*O}] [\*L-fast\*O]
.iE
.P
The \*L-cell \*Vcellname\*O option specifies the name of a foreign cell
whose File Server machines the Cache Manager is to check.  The Cache Manager
determines the status of each File Server machine with which it has been
in contact from the specified cell.  Use the \*L\-cell\*O option or use the
\*L\-all\*O option to direct the Cache Manager to check File Server machines
in all cells; omit both options to check the status of each File Server
machine the Cache Manager has contacted from the local cell only.
.nL
.ne 20
.P
The \*L-all\*O option directs the command to check the status of each File
Server machine with which it has been in contact, regardless of the cell in
which a machine resides.  Use the \*L\-all\*O option or use the \*L\-cell\*O
option to specify a specific foreign cell whose File Server machines the
Cache Manager is to check; omit both options to check the status of each
File Server machine the Cache Manager has contacted from the local cell only.
.P
The \*L-fast\*O option directs the command to display the results of its
most recent probes.  The Cache Manager does not probe File Server machines to
determine their statuses at the instant the command is issued.
.P
If all of the File Server machines that it probes respond, the Cache Manager
displays the following output in response to the command:
.oS
All servers are running.
.oE
.P
If one or more of the File Server machines that it probes do not respond, the
Cache Manager displays the following output:
.oS
\*CThese servers are still down: \*Vhostname\*O
.oE
.P
.zA "enh,13566,R1.2.2,Add multihomed server"
where \*Vhostname\*O is the name of each File Server machine that fails to
respond. In a multihomed server environment, the
\*Vhostname\*O corresponds to the machine name that the Cache Manager is
currently using to access each File Server machine.  The output does
not contain multiple machine host names for the same File Server machine. 
.zZ "enh,13566,R1.2.2,Add multihomed server"
.iX "-]" "Cache Manager" "checking File Server status"
.iX "-]" "File Server machines" "checking status"
.zA "enh, 13605, R1.2.2, Security enhancements"
.H 3 "RPC Authentication Level Configuration"
You can set the RPC authentication level for communications between the Cache Manager and File Servers.  By default, such communications use the packet integrity DCE RPC authentication level (each RPC is authenticated and the data is checked to ensure that it was not modified in transit). However, circumstances at your site may require higher security or permit lower security for File Server communications.  The following lists the range of authentication levels: 
.P
.VL
.LI "Default"
Use the DCE default authentication level.
.LI "None"
Perform no authentication.
.LI "Connect" 
Authenticate only when the Cache Manager establishes a connection with the File Server.
.LI  "Call"
Authenticate only at the beginning of each RPC received.
.LI "Packet"
Ensure that all data received is from the expected host (authenticate).
.LI "Packet Integrity"
.nL
Ensure that all data received is from the expected host and verify that none of the data has been modified.
.LI "Packet Privacy"
.nL
Perform authentication as specified by all of the previous levels and also encrypt each RPC argument value.
.LE
.P
Note that higher authentication levels do incur some overhead and therefore cause some degradation in performance.  Lower security levels, while more efficient, do carry an additional risk of attack.
.P
You can set separate authentication levels for dealing with File Servers in the local cell and for dealing with File Servers in foreign cells.  These authentication levels are set through two pairs of values. Each pair of values consists of the following:
.ML
.LI
An initial RPC authentication level.  This value sets the initial RPC authentication level used by the Cache Manager when it attempts to establish communications with a File Server. The initial level is used as a starting point in negotiating an RPC authentication level with the File Server.
.LI
A minimum RPC authentication level.  This value defines a lower bound RPC authentication level for the Cache Manager.  Should a File Server request an authentication level below this level, the Cache Manager will refuse communications with that File Server.
.LE
.P
For a complete description of how the Cache Manager negotiates the RPC authentication level, see Section 2.5.  In short, each File Server (File Exporter) maintains its own pairs of security values.  These pairs set maximum and minimum bounds that control RPC authentication for communications with Cache Managers.  As with the Cache Manager, one pair controls communications with Cache Managers within the local cell while the other controls communications with Cache Managers in foreign cells.  By default, the RPC authentication settings at the File Server and Cache Manager will negotiate to the packet integrity authentication level.
.P
The Cache Manager begins the negotiation by sending an RPC to the File Server at the authentication level determined by its initial RPC setting.  The File Manager then replies in one of the following three ways:
.ML
.LI
The File Server accepts the RPC authentication level it received (the level fell within the range defined by its upper and lower bounds) and begins the process of sending and receiving fileset data with the Cache Manager.
.LI
The File Server finds that the RPC authentication level is above its upper bound and sends a response to the Cache Manager instructing it to lower its authentication level.  If the Cache Manager is currently using an authentication level equal to the Cache Manager's lower bound, the Cache Manager will cease attempts to communicate with the File Server.
.LI
The File Server finds that the RPC authentication level is below its lower bound and sends a response to the Cache Manager instructing it to raise its authentication level.
.LE
.P
The following sections detail how to initially configure the Cache Manager RPC authentication levels and how to adjust those levels for a running Cache Manager.
.H 4 "Configuring RPC Authentication Levels"
.P
The default Cache Manager and File Server authentication settings are such that they will negotiate to the packet integrity authentication level.  Use the following options to set the authentication levels at the Cache Manager:
.ML
.LI 
\*L-initiallocalprotectlevel\*O - Specifies the initial DCE RPC authentication 
level for communications between the Cache Manager and File Servers
within the local cell. 
.LI 
\*L-minlocalprotectlevel\*O - Specifies the minimum acceptable DCE RPC authentication level for communications between the Cache Manager and File Servers within the
local cell. 
.LI 
\*L-initialremoteprotectlevel\*O - Specifies the initial DCE RPC authentication level for communications between the Cache Manager and File Servers within foreign cells.
.LI 
\*L-minremoteprotectlevel\*O -
Specifies the minimum acceptable DCE RPC authentication level for
communications between the Cache Manager and File Servers within
foreign cells. 
.LE
.P
Each of the above options takes either a string, abbreviated string, or integer value as an argument to define the RPC authentication level.  The following lists the values you can use:
.P
.ML
.LI
\*Lrpc_protect_level_default\*O or \*Ldefault\*O or \*L0\*O: Use the DCE default authentication level.
.LI 
\*Lrpc_protect_level_none\*O or \*Lnone\*O or \*L1\*O: Perform no authentication.
.LI 
\*Lrpc_protect_level_connect\*O or \*Lconnect\*O or \*L2\*O: Authenticate only when the Cache Manager establishes a connection with the File Server.
.LI 
\*Lrpc_protect_level_call\*O or \*Lcall\*O or \*L3\*O: Authenticate only at the beginning of each RPC received.
.LI 
\*Lrpc_protect_level_pkt\*O or \*Lpkt\*O or \*L4\*O: Ensure that all data received is from the expected host.
.LI 
\*Lrpc_protect_level_pkt_integrity\*O or \*Lpkt_integrity\*O or \*L5\*O: Authenticate and verify that none of the
data transferred has been modified.
.LI
\*Lrpc_protect_level_pkt_privacy\*O or \*Lpkt_privacy\*O or \*L6\*O: Perform authentication as specified by all of the previous levels and also encrypt each RPC argument value.
.LE 
.P
The following example sets the initial RPC authentication level for the home cell to connect, the minimum authentication RPC level for the home cell to none, the initial RPC authentication level for foreign cells to packet privacy, and the minimum authentication level for foreign cells also to packet privacy.
.oS
\*C$ \*Ldfsd -initiallocalprotectlevel rpc_protect_level_connect -\minlocalprotectlevel 
.NL
none -initialremoteprotectlevel 6 -initialremoteprotectlevel pkt_privacy\*O
.oE
.P
When configuring the authentication levels, any combination of \*Ldfsd\*O options is allowed.
.P
.H 4 "Changing the RPC Authentication Levels Temporarily"
.P
You can reset any of the RPC authentication levels without rebooting the machine by using the \*Lcm setprotectlevels\*O command. The values you alter remain in effect until you next reboot the machine. 
.P
To change the authentication levels temporarily, do the following:
.P
.AL
.LI
Log in as \*Lroot\*O on the machine.
.LI
Issue the \*Lcm setprotectlevels\*O command with the appropriate options.
.LE
.iS
\*C# \*Lcm setprotectlevels\*O [\*L-initiallocalprotectlevel\*O \*Vlevel\*O]
[\*L-minlocalprotectlevel\*O \*Vlevel\*O] 
.nL
[\*L\-initialremoteprotectlevel\*O \*Vlevel\*O] [\*L-minremoteprotectlevel\*L \*Vlevel\*O] 
.iE
.P
The various options are defined as follows:
.VL
.LI "\*L-initiallocalprotectlevel\*O \*Vlevel\*O" - 
Specifies the initial DCE RPC authentication 
level for communications between the Cache Manager and File Servers
within the same cell. 
.LI "\*L-minlocalprotectlevel\*O \*Vlevel\*O" - 
Specifies the minimum acceptable DCE RPC authentication level for
communications between the Cache Manager and File Servers within the
same cell. 
.LI "\*L-initialremoteprotectlevel \*Vlevel\*O" - 
Specifies the initial DCE RPC authentication level for 
communications between the Cache Manager and File Servers within foreign cells.
.LI "\*L-minremoteprotectlevel \*Vlevel\*O" - 
Specifies the minimum acceptable DCE RPC authentication level for
communications between the Cache Manager and File Servers within
foreign cells. 
.LE
.P
Where \*Vlevel\*O is the appropriate RPC authentication level. The various levels can be set by specifying a complete string, an abbreviated string, or a corresponding integer value.  The valid arguments for \*Vlevel\*O are defined in Section 5.12.1.1.
.P
The following example command
.ML
.LI
Sets the initial authentication level for communications
with File Servers in the local cell to packet integrity.
.LI
Sets the minimum authentication level for communications with File Servers in 
the local cell to packet.
.LI
Sets the initial authentication level for communications with File Servers in foreign cells to packet privacy.
.LI
Sets the minimum authentication level for communications with File Servers in 
foreign cells to packet privacy.
.LE
.PP
.iS
\*C$\*O \*Lcm setprotectlevels -initiallocalprotectlevel pkt_integ 
-minlocalprotectlevel 4
-initialremoteprotectlevel 6 -minremoteprotectlevel 6\*O 
.iE
.P
.H 4 "Checking RPC Authentication Levels"
.P
You can check the Cache Manager's current RPC authentication levels by using the \*Lcm getprotectlevels\*O command:
.iS
\*C$ \*Lcm getprotectlevels\*O
.iE
.oS
\*CInitial protection level in the local cell: \*Vvalue\*O 
\*CMinimum protection level in the local cell: \*Vvalue\*O
\*CInitial protection level in non-local cells: \*Vvalue\*O
\*CMinimum protection level in non-local cells: \*Vvalue\*O
.oE
.P
The various possible output strings for \*Vvalue\*O are as follows:
.P
.ML
.LI
\*Lrpc_c_protect_level_default\*O - default
.LI 
\*Lrpc_c_protect_level_none\*O - none
.LI
\*Lrpc_c_protect_level_connect\*O - connect
.LI 
\*Lrpc_c_protect_level_call\*O - call
.LI 
\*Lrpc_c_protect_level_pkt\*O - packet
.LI 
\*Lrpc_c_protect_level_pkt_integ\*O - packet integrity
.LI
\*Lrpc_c_protect_level_pkt_privacy\*O - packet privacy
.LE 
.zZ "enh, 13605, R1.2.2, Security enhancements"